This is a classic interview question 👍
Merge two sorted arrays into one sorted array

✅ Problem
arr1 = [1,3,5,7]
arr2 = [2,4,6,8]

Output:

[1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8]
🔥 Optimal Solution (Two Pointer – O(n + m))

This is the correct interview approach, not using .sort.

def merge_sorted_arrays(arr1, arr2)
  i = 0
  j = 0
  result = []

  while i < arr1.length && j < arr2.length
    if arr1[i] <= arr2[j]
      result << arr1[i]
      i += 1
    else
      result << arr2[j]
      j += 1
    end
  end

  # Add remaining elements
  while i < arr1.length
    result << arr1[i]
    i += 1
  end

  while j < arr2.length
    result << arr2[j]
    j += 1
  end

  result
end

p merge_sorted_arrays([1,3,5,7], [2,4,6,8])
🧠 How It Works

We compare elements from both arrays:

1 vs 2 → take 1
3 vs 2 → take 2
3 vs 4 → take 3
...

Once one array is exhausted, we append remaining elements.

⏱ Complexity

Time: O(n + m)
Space: O(n + m)

⚠ Interview Trap

Many candidates do this:

(arr1 + arr2).sort

❌ That is O((n+m) log(n+m))

Interviewer wants linear merge logic.

💎 In-Place Version (If Allowed to Modify arr1)

